model_explanation: S1 states that the only person who got grapes from Sam was Bill, while S2 introduces another recipient, Sue, contradicting the exclusivity asserted in S1.
S1 establishes that Sue is the sole recipient of oranges, and S2 contradicts that by saying Rob also received oranges, violating the exclusivity from S1.
S1 implies that Sue is the only recipient of grapes, which aligns with S2’s statement confirming that Ellen did not receive grapes.
S1 asserts that apples were the only thing Tom received, and S2 is consistent with that by confirming that Tom didn’t get any grapes.
S1 limits what Rob received to only oranges, whereas S2 contradicts that by adding apples as another item Rob received.
S1 says Sue is the only recipient of grapes, and S2 supports that by confirming that Tom, in fact, got no grapes.

S1 says Ellen is the only recipient of bananas, and S2 introduces Mary as another recipient, which is independent and does not uphold or negate the exclusivity about Ellen receiving bananas. It adds new information.
S1 is about bananas given exclusively to Rob, while S2 is about oranges not given to Rob. These statements are about different items and are independent.
S1 states that bananas are the only thing Mary received, while S2 contradicts that by introducing apples as another received item.
S1 limits the orange-giving to Sue alone, and S2 simply reports that Rob didn’t get any oranges. These statements do not overlap in a way that entails or contradicts—they operate independently.
